<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-881-882  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 881 882.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  August 1989 v36 n8 p34(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Control system design: part 4 - the man/machine interface;designing interactive graphics.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Gerald R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The design of interactive graphics-based control system userinterfaces requires keeping the user's needs and behaviors in mindto achieve effective interactions (understanding and response)with the control system.andP;  The interface must be implemented on thebasis of conventions that make maximum use of human intuition.andO;These conventions address: layout, location and orientation of thedisplay; data representation; operator action operations; andsystem responses.andP;  The display design must offer a hierarchy ofincreasing levels of information and detail oriented to thevarying levels and kinds of users.andP;  Priorities of information mustbe indicated: first, the health of the particular control process;second, the process data itself; and third, process values, setpoints and modes.andP;  Information presentation must be optimized forclarity of flow but also provide exception handling.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Control SystemsSystem DesignRequirements AnalysisInteractive SystemsGraphical User InterfaceGraphics SystemsProcess ControlUser NeedsTutorial.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>